metadata.name: Estimation #32
metadata.description:
Exceeding sensor resolution / pt. 2

Estimation (or estimating) is the process of finding an estimate or approximation, which is a value that is usable for some purpose even if input data may be incomplete, uncertain, or unstable. The value is nonetheless usable because it is derived from the best information available. Typically, estimation involves "using the value of a statistic derived from a sample to estimate the value of a corresponding population parameter".

metadata.name: Calmer waters - reissue #4
metadata.description:
This is a reissue of project #10669
https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/10669

I long for calmer waters. This piece is about that. It's a counterpoint. It reflects some of my best memories of the sea: the warm salty air on my face, interspersed with a cool breeze, leaving my lips salty tasting. The gentle rushing of the water. 

The sea with its vast panorama's can make you feel insignificant in the grand scheme of things. But this piece is about hope.
///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
About this reissue: An update of the security policy of fx(hash) blocks external scripts. This update stops malicious actors; they could try to interact with a user‚Äôs wallet. So, this update is really a good thing. It‚Äôs a safeguard. However, due to this update the original project no longer loads in live view and after consultation and deliberation I decided to reissue the token without the use of external scripts (p5js). 

Only holders of the original project are on the allow list. 

Royalties are for the minter.

metadata.name: A Strange Loop #143
metadata.description:
[ TAP/CLICK TO ACTIVATE SOUND ]

A whiff of pattern begins to emerge. Out of disarray comes the familiar pulsation of an ordered signal. The sense of regularity strengthens and we feel it swelling towards a singularity. Heeere weeee goooo‚Ä¶ BAM! Then off again marching back into chaos to repeat the cycle.

Proposed by cognitive scientist Douglas Hofstadter in his 1979 book ‚ÄúG√∂del, Escher, Bach‚Äù, and further developed in his 2007 book ‚ÄúI Am a Strange Loop‚Äù, ‚ÄúStrange Loops‚Äù are Hofstadter‚Äôs attempt at explaining the mechanisms that give rise to the sensation of ‚ÄúI‚Äù - through hierarchical, self-referential, and at times seemingly paradoxical feedback-loops of abstraction and causality. 

‚Äî

‚ÄúWho shoves whom around in the tangled megaganglion that is your brain, and who shoves whom around in ‚Äòthis teetering bulb of dread and dream‚Äô that is mine?‚Äù

‚ÄúDo dreads and dreams, hopes and griefs, ideas and beliefs, interests and doubts, infatuations and envies, memories and ambitions, bouts of nostalgia and floods of empathy, flashes of guilt and sparks of genius, play any role in the world of physical objects? Do such pure abstractions have causal powers? Can they shove massive things around, or are they just impotent fictions?‚Äù 

"In the end, we are self-perceiving, self-inventing, locked-in mirages that are little miracles of self-reference. [...] Poised midway between the unvisualizable cosmic vastness of curved spacetime and the dubious, shadowy flickerings of charged quanta, we human beings, more like rainbows and mirages than like raindrops or boulders, are unpredictable self-writing poems ‚Äî vague, metaphorical, ambiguous, and sometimes exceedingly beautiful.‚Äù

- Douglas Hofstadter, ‚ÄúI Am a Strange Loop‚Äù, 2007

‚Äì-

metadata.name: Spring flowers #N #3
metadata.description:
‚ÄúSpring flowers‚Äù is a generative art series conceived in Kyiv in March 2025, under the tender influence of the city‚Äôs blooming spring. This work captures the delicate essence of renewal and the vibrant pulse of nature awakening, drawing inspiration from Andy Warhol‚Äôs iconic Flowers series. Like Warhol‚Äôs bold yet playful exploration of floral forms, this series reimagines blossoms through a digital lens, infusing them with a soft, watercolor effect that evokes the gentle breath of spring in Kyiv.

Each piece unfolds as a unique composition of five abstract flowers, their petals painted with fluid, translucent hues‚Äîvibrant corals, sunny yellows, serene blues, and lush greens‚Äîset against a subtle, pastel background. The black centers of the flowers, fading into airy grays, mimic the organic diffusion of watercolor on paper, while animated particles drift across the canvas, embodying the breeze that carries spring‚Äôs promise. This interplay of stillness and motion reflects the harmony of nature‚Äôs cycles, blending algorithmic precision with the spontaneity of hand-painted art.

Why Collect?
Unique Generative Creations: Every artwork is algorithmically distinct, offering collectors an exclusive piece of digital flora.

*Warholian Echoes: A modern nod to Andy Warhol‚Äôs Flowers, merging pop art legacy with cutting-edge generative techniques.
*Kyiv‚Äôs Spring Spirit: Created amidst Kyiv‚Äôs blossoming season, it encapsulates a moment of beauty and resilience.
*Own a piece of ‚ÄúSpring flowers‚Äù  ‚Äî a celebration of spring‚Äôs fleeting magic, rooted in Kyiv‚Äôs vibrant soul and the timeless allure of watercolor blooms.

***
Press S or double-click to save as PNG.

***

Kyiv, 17.03.2025

metadata.name: Cave Etchings #187
metadata.description:
Cave Etchings are detailed line drawings generated from unedited AI images of caves, conjoining an AI process with a generative art process. The project is not just an exercise in aesthetics, it is about seeing things the way a computer 'sees'. The original AI cave series focused on how AI Computer Vision can imagine fantastical caves; in cave etchings, the software visualises pixel data as movement, rotating lines according to hue, saturation, and brightness values. The project is inspired by the artwork of Franklin Booth (1874- 1948).
More details here: https://www.plummerfernandez.com/works/cave-etchings/

metadata.name: Xel I-II #13
metadata.description:
We‚Äôve always known wallet addresses as strings of letters and numbers, Dry, soulless data, yet always present.
But what if this presence could breathe?

In the enhanced, living version of "Season One", we revisit that same idea, transforming the blockchain‚Äôs most essential elements into evolving pixelated lifeforms.
Each artwork is still generated from the wallet address (`fxminter`) and the token‚Äôs hash (`fxhash`), but the project pulses with a new kind of energy this time.

### What‚Äôs new in this evolved version:

üï∞ A Magical Clock
A real-time clock has been embedded into the artwork. One that only ticks forward with each new mint.
Each minted token captures a unique minute in time, held eternally by its collector.
This enchanted clock is not merely decorative. It holds a secret that will only be fully unveiled in "Season Two".

üß© A Fragment of the Bigger Picture
Alongside the creature, every mint now receives a Roman numeral representing its mint number and a coordinate, marking its position in a hidden puzzle.
Each token is a piece of a larger design; together, these fragments will reconstruct the gateway to the next season.

üß¨ Multiple Perspectives, One Identity
The core pixel creature, still generated uniquely from your wallet and hash, now appears in three views:

* a breathing 2D form rendered in real time,
* a puzzled isometric shape,
* and a miniature preview of the final Season Two puzzle form, hinting at what‚Äôs to come.
  Your identity is no longer shown from a single angle, it‚Äôs a multidimensional expression.

üé® Colors from the Hash, Signatures from the Wallet
Like in the original version, all color palettes are derived directly from the hash. No two are alike.
And, as always, your wallet address is subtly signed beneath the artwork, a permanent mark of authorship.

---

This is not Season Two.
This is Season One: Alive, an evolved, living version of the original.
It preserves everything that made the first release special, but adds movement, time, spatial positioning, and hints of the next chapter.

If Season One was a spark, this version is its flame.
Only holders of these tokens will be able to step fully into Season Two and witness the transformation of their piece into its final narrative form.
Until then, this is your moment. Your pixel, your minute, your breath in the story.

Reptile ü¶é
----------

metadata.name: Resilience  #137
metadata.description:
Resilience is a collection of endless architectures.
In a resilient generative system composed of multiple compatible parts, real-time information exchange enables open reconfigurations and continuous discrete adjustments. Sometimes vague and fuzzy, sometimes real and tangible, they reveal different readings of architectural complexity and scale: from city plans to floor plans and details to sections and elevations.

Resilience comes in a variety of polychrome palettes, ascii glyphs, and styles. 
To enjoy it in full-screen mode, press the left mouse button in live mode, for a monochrome look press 'b'. Made with P5js.

Resilience Generative Token by @grasser_alex 2022

metadata.name: Bento Boxes #77
metadata.description:
Everybody needs a bento box in the cryptowinter.
The project calls for an adopted nostalgia of little kids that has been handed bento box by their parents before school‚Äî a little moment of protected comfort before heading out for an adventure.

‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢

The first collaboration project of MEK.txt and IceRain in FXHash. A work based on MEK.txt‚Äôs ‚ÄúThe Bento Boxes‚Äù and IceRain‚Äôs excellent codes, Bento Boxes aims to be a fun visual and code exploration project on the generative art corridor. Pure code, no libraries.

Bento Boxes deconstructed the visual system on MEK.txt's artwork, titled almost similarly, ‚ÄúThe Bento Boxes‚Äù. Rebuilt it from scratch with codes, adding variants of colours and shapes‚Äî without losing the strong characteristics of the base artwork.

metadata.name: Trame communale #2
metadata.description:
What does it mean to live together? What is the plan? What are we doing here? By that, I do not mean that I want to know what you are doing as an individual person, but rather what the whole of us is to achieve. Am I responsible for myself or am I responsible for you too? Am I responsible for what every single person does, or for what we collectively do as a group? Both? Neither? 

What does it mean to live together?

===

Trame communale is a generative architecture project.

The generator is made to produce 64 iterations of buildings whose structures are consistent with most plastic bricks brands.

Iterations can be virtually loaded in the anaverse under a new "village" system, which loads them all in a same space (positioned according to their order of creation).

Every owner inhabits the same commune.
